<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aziz Attacks Butler's Statements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Premier Tariq
Aziz today lashed out at chief U.N. arms inspector Richard Butler,
calling his statements "inaccurate and unobjective."
</P>
<P>
Aziz accused Butler of moving ahead "with a spree of inaccurate
and unobjective statements" on his Baghdad talks, thereby serving
the American plan aimed at unjustifiably scaling up the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Butler said on Friday in New York that he had reasons to doubt
that Iraq was hiding prohibited materials at "presidential and
sovereign sites."
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that U.N. arms inspectors had actually carried out
119 inspections of national security-related locations during
1996 and 1997 upon receiving information similar to those cited
in Butler's statements, but found nothing.
</P>
<P>
"I asked him (Butler) in Baghdad if that was not enough to
construe that the information on the basis of which inspection had
been made were groundless and misleading," said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
The deputy premier said he reminded Butler of a British
newspaper revelation about a meeting between Israel's intelligence
service Mossad and the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM)
on disarming Iraq reportedly held to provide UNSCOM with such
information.
</P>
<P>
It was a right decision to videotape the talks, said Aziz,
expressing confidence that the attendance of Russian, French and
British representatives at the talks would largely contribute to
revealing the facts.
</P>
<P>
Butler held three rounds of talks with Iraqi officials during
his four-day visit to Baghdad from December 12-16, but failed to
persuade Iraq to allow U.N. arms inspectors' access to the
presidential sites, which Iraq views as symbols of national
sovereignty and dignity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
