<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French PM Lays Out New Africa Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 20 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin, who is on his first tour to Africa, presented France's new
Africa policy on Saturday in the Senegalese capital of Dakar.
</P>
<P>
Jospin said that the new approach is based on the "adaptation
of the tools of cooperation" to the present era. He promised that
France would not "do less", but will "do better" in its
cooperation with African countries.
</P>
<P>
"France does not say or think that the time of aid is past," he
said, following talks with Senegalese President Abdou Diouf, and
Senegalese Prime Minister Habib Thiam.
</P>
<P>
Jospin assured the Franco-zone nations of Africa that the
launching of the European single currency will not affect them.
</P>
<P>
On international affairs, Jospin promised that France would
continue to serve as the "lawyer" of Africa in seeking
international aid for the continent.
</P>
<P>
France will ask the international community to contribute to
the building of an African peace-keeping force through the
"Reinforcement of African Capacities for the Maintenance of
Peace", to be jointly launched by the European Union and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The French prime minister said that as part of the preparations
for the force, France will provide the complete equipment for a
battalion of troops and a military field hospital for
Senegal. This will be done in February when French troops jointly
hold military maneuvers with their Senegalese, Mauritanian and
Malian counterparts.
</P>
<P>
He said France could not ensure by itself the security of its
African partners, and hoped to reinforce the inter-African
cooperation in security through multilateral military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of emigration by Africans to France, Jospin said
Paris hoped African governments could take measures to control
this.
</P>
<P>
France would also soften its policy on visa issues, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
