<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Prime Minister to Chair Welfare Working Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 20 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair said today that he is to chair a new government working
party on reforming the welfare state.
</P>
<P>
Blair made the announcement in a speech to an audience in his
Sedgefield constituency, saying "the party that created the
welfare state is the party that is going to have to reform it."
</P>
<P>
He said the system created with such pride in 1945 by the
post-war Labor government had been left behind by changes in
society.
</P>
<P>
Blair, fighting rebels in his party over cuts in welfare
payment, said the current 100 billion pounds (166 billion US
dollars) a year cost of the welfare state neither relieved poverty
nor delivered the investment needed for the future.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also said benefit fraud was costing 5
billion pounds (8 billion US dollars) a year, but he pledged help
would continue for the poorest.
</P>
<P>
He said the reforms would aim to relieve poverty, narrow social
division, extend opportunity and help the poor rather than punish
them.
</P>
<P>
"There can't be any backing down. It is essential that we make
these reforms," Blair insisted.
</P>
<P>
Last week 47 Labor MPs voted against cuts in benefit payments
for lone parents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
