<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Chinese into Singles Finals at ITTF Pro-Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Three Chinese have qualified
for the men's and women's singles finals following their victories
in the semi-finals at the 1997 International Table Tennis
Federation Pro-Tour Grand Finals here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Wang Liqin, 19, who made himself known after his stunning
victory over Sweden's world champion Jan-Ove Waldner on Friday,
scored an fairly easy 21-10, 21-19, 21-10 semi-final victory
Saturday over Belgian Jean-Michel Saive, now ranked 13th in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Saive beat China's defending champion Kong Linghui in the
quarter-finals on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"I won because I'd taken the initiative today," said the
Chinese teenager from Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Saive, 28, said he could not play his game today. "I was not
waken as I almost did not sleep last night," he said.
</P>
<P>
The aggressive Belgian said he did not know much about the
Chinese opponent before. "They (Chinese) might have 2,000 copies
of tapes of my matches and I, as a European, could feel very
difficult in playing a Chinese for the first time," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I wasn't playing my game today. If I could have played as
yesterday and the before, I could win over anyone," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
Cai Zhenhua, Head Coach of the Chinese team, said Wang should
owe his victory to his better tactics today. He admitted that his
team was in a better position as they had known a lot about Saive.
</P>
<P>
"Saive was managing throughout the match today to get the game
of Wang," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang is to play in Sunday's final Vladimir Samsonov from
Belarus, who eliminated Zoran Primorac of Croatia 23-21, 12-21,
21-17, 22-20 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Samsonov had won over Wang three times and lost once before.
</P>
<P>
China's world number two and top seed here Li Ju qualified for
the women's singles final after beating Park Hae Jung from South
Korea 21-8, 21-19, 22-24, 21-12 in the semi-finals today.
</P>
<P>
Li's victory set an all-Chinese final as China's world
runner-up and world number three Wang Nan eliminated South Korea's
Ryu Ji Hye 21-9, 21-19, 21-18 today.
</P>
<P>
China has one pair each into the men's and women's doubles
finals. Kong Linhui teamed with Olympic champion Liu Guoliang to
beat Patrick Chila/Christophe Legout from France 21-8, 16-21,
21-17, 21-12 for a berth in the men's doubles final.
</P>
<P>
And the German-Belarussian combination of Jorg Rosskopf and
Vladimir Samsonov downed Chinese Wang Liqin and Yan Sen 21-19,
16-21, 11-21, 21-19, 21-17 in the semi-finals today.
</P>
<P>
The qualifier for the women's doubles final were Chinese Li
Ju/Wang Nan and South Korea's Park Hae Jung/Kim Moo Kyu. They
beat their compatriots Cheng Hongxia/Wang Hui and Ryu Ji Hye/Lee
Eun Sil in the semi-finals on Saturday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
