<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Denies Border Disputes with Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean officials have
denied allegations of border disputes with Mozambique in the
eastern highlands following reports that some Zimbabwean farmers
were altering border markers to extend their farms eastwards.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe News Agency today quoted officials in the
country's Ministry of Foreign Affairs as saying that they had not
received any imformation about border disputes from
the offical channel of Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The Maputo daily Noticias reported recently that Zimbabwean
farmers were altering border markers and pushing their lands
deeper into Mozambique in an attempt to extend their farms.
</P>
<P>
The farmers are reportedly planting tea and coffee on
Mozambican soil.
</P>
<P>
Negion Moyo, Deputy Provincial Criminal Investigations Officer
of Zimbabwe's Manicaland Province, said the police had not
received any such complaints from the Mozambicans.
</P>
<P>
"There could be some communal farmers encroaching onto the
Mozambican land. These people along the border, because of their
cross border relations, can do anything but we can not declare
that a border dispute," Moyo noted.
</P>
<P>
"If there was an issue of that nature it would have been
brought to our attention," the officer said, adding "These may be
isolated cases."
</P>
<P>
According to Mozambican officials, maps of the conventional
limits between the two countries could be consulted to sort out
the facts if things worsened, reported the news agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
