<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Hands over Party Leadership to Mbeki </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 20 (Xinhua) -- As the five-day national
conference of South Africa's ruling African National Congress
(ANC) concluded today, former ANC president Nelson Mandela handed
over a symbolic baton of leadership to his successor Thabo Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said, as the 1999 general election draws near along
with his departure from the national presidency, he would try to
delegate increasing responsibility to Mbeki to ensure a smooth
transition, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
As Mandela would not seek re-election in 1999, it is generally
believed that Mbeki will become the next state president.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, who has been left to run the day-to-day work of the
government, is the de facto president of the country.
</P>
<P>
According to Mandela, Mbeki's unopposed election as ANC
president at the conference was a fitting tribute to his
performance in various capacities in exile, the impressive
contribution he made as part of the ANC team at the Codesa
settlement talks, and the brilliant way in which he had carried
out his duties as deputy president of the ANC and of the
government.
</P>
<P>
The Codesa (Convention for a Democratic South Africa) talks in
the early 1990s, helped bring about the end of apartheid in South
Africa and heralded the first all-race elections in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, in a closing speech of the conference, chanted eulogies
to his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
"Once more, many thanks, Madiba (Mandela's clan name), for who
you are, for what you are, for what you have done for us and for
our people."
</P>
<P>
"The happiness of your people will be your reward, the loyalty
of the members to the traditions of your movement, your pride."
</P>
<P>
The national conference ended today with a soccer match that
overwhelmed planned speeches of Mandela and Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
The speeches were canceled at the last minute at a rally in a
stadium in Mafikeng when ANC leaders realized that soccer
fanaticism had won over political rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
ANC supporters at the rally were excited at the sight of their
soccer teams when the rally began.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to cater for the large local and international
media contingent, Mandela approached the podium to deliver his
prepared speech, but was interrupted when the crowd erupted again
at the sight of the Orlando Pirates soccer team strolling on to
the pitch.
</P>
<P>
Mandela then strode to the reporters to read part of his
speech instead.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki declined to deliver his prepared speech for fear that
the restless crowd might get out of hand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
