<HEADLINE> Drug Use Among Teen-Agers Remains Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Drug use among teen-agers
in the United States remained stable and the number of high
school seniors who use marijuana was on the rise last year,
according to a U.S. annual federal survey.
</P>
<P>
The use of illegal drugs among eighth graders was steady from
1996 to 1997, with the exceptions of marijuana, cigarettes and
heroin, which showed a slight decrease in use, the Department of
Health and Human Services (HHS) said in a report released today.
</P>
<P>
The number of 10th and 12th graders who used drugs in the past
year or months was also stable. However, reported daily use of
marijuana by high school seniors rose from 4.9 percent in 1996 to
5.8 percent this year, the department said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton today called on parents to make
efforts to prevent children from using drugs.
</P>
<P>
"The most effective strategy we have against drugs begins at
home. It's a fight that can be won at kitchen tables all across
America," Clinton said in his weekly radio appearance.
</P>
<P>
"This holiday season, as we spend some hard-earned time with
our families, I urge all parents to sit down with their children,
as Hillary and I have done, and share a simple and important
lesson: Drugs are dangerous, drugs are wrong and drugs can kill,"
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
The HHS said the possible slowdown of illicit drug use among
young people is encouraging, even though rates of use remain
unacceptably high. But it said parents and teachers need to
redouble their efforts to make young people understand that drug
abuse is illegal, dangerous and wrong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
