<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Oil Sector Needs 90 b Dollar in 10 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 20 (Xinhua) -- An oil expert has predicted
Iran needs about 90 billion dollars of investment for the oil
industry in the coming 10 years to preserve its present output,
local daily Etelaat reported today.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Iranian Economists' Association Manouchehr
Farhang made the remark at a monthly gathering of the association,
adding that Iran enjoys 10 percent of the world's oil reserves and
20 percent of the world's gas reserves.
</P>
<P>
At present, Iran has a crude production of 3.6 million barrels
per day (bpd) and the figure will be increased to 3.94 million bpd
as of next year under the new quota made by the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) last month.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Zanganeh said earlier that his
country expected 5 billion dollars of investment for onshore and
offshore oil fields every year after the National Iranian Oil
Company (NIOC) signed a buyback agreement with the French Total in
September.
</P>
<P>
Farhang said that the buyback agreement between NIOC and Total
would help better exploit the country's oil and gas resources and
consolidate the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The buyback agreement will inject 2 billion dollars by Total
into Iran's South Pars gas field project, he said, encouraging the
Iranian government to sign more buyback agreements with foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
"Once the South Pars gas field project takes wing, it will
produce 80,000 barrels per day of natural gas and the main loan
plus interests will be repaid to the foreign side within a period
of seven years," Farhang said. That gas field was reported to have
240 trillion cubic feet of gas deposits.
</P>
<P>
He attacked the U.S. economic sanctions on Iran, saying "had we
not been under sanctions, it would have been better to sign a
joint capital investment venture with a foreign company so that
the foreign partner would have been committed to guarantee its
execution and share the profits as well as the losses."
</P>
<P>
However, former deputy oil minister for international affairs,
Hadi Nejat Husseinian, told the gathering that the reason for the
lack of foreign joint investment in Iran's oil projects was that
the country's laws do not allow foreign participation in such
projects.
</P>
<P>
This is aimed at protecting Iran's national sovereignty over
these projects, he explained, by signing buyback agreements, Iran
would be the sole owner of the project whereas in a joint venture
both partners will work until the project is exhausted.
</P>
<P>
The IEA was formed five years ago with members from professors
and students of economic sciences. It holds monthly meetings to
discuss the country's economic issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
