<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German, Italian Insurance Giants Strike Deal Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Germany's largest insurance
company Allianz AG and its Italian counterpart, Assicurazioni
Generali SpA, have struck a deal over the takeover of the third
largest French insurer Assurances Generales de France SA (AGF),
said news reports today.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal announced by the companies Friday evening,
Allianz will buy AGF for 320 French francs (53.60 U.S. dollars) a
share and sell part of AGF's newly-acquired insurance group Athena
to Generali.
</P>
<P>
Allianz, which is relatively weak in France, would become the
second biggest insurer in the country under the arrangement,
analysts said. The deal could also allow Allianz to recapture the
title as Europe's largest insurer it lost last year after the
merger of French insurers Axa SA and Union des Assurances de
France.
</P>
<P>
As part of the deal, Generali will also buy the shares owned by
Allianz and AGF in the Aachener and Muenchener Beteiligungs AG,
giving Generali a controlling stake in the third-largest insurer
of Germany.
</P>
<P>
The latest agreement represented a cease-fire between Allianz
and Generali which were battling with each other to take over AGF
over the past two months.
</P>
<P>
Both Allianz and Generali said today that they were satisfied
with the accord because it would gave them a better position in
France and Germany respectively.
</P>
<P>
The takeover deal over AGF is also the latest of a series of
acquisitions in the European insurance industry in the past year
as companies rushed to prepare themselves for a wider single
market to be ushered in by the planned single European currency,
the Euro.
</P>
<P>
The planned introduction of the Euro in 1999 would make it
easier for companies to sell the same products in countries that
share the currency and eliminate exchange-rate costs in the
region, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
They also predicted that only a handful of firms would dominate
Europe's lucrative insurance business in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
