<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Report on Rushdie Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Iran today denied its reported
readiness to issue a written guarantee not to make any attempt on
the lift of British writer Salman Rushdie, who was condemned to
death by Iran's late spiritual leader Ayatollah Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
The British Independent newspaper reported Iran's Minister of
Culture and Islamic Guidance Ataollah Mohajerani has said Tehran
is ready to issue such a guarantee to spare the life of Rushdie,
accused of blasphemy to Islam for his novel the "Satanic Verses."
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance
said Mohajerani only reiterated the country's stand that the
decree by Khomeini is irrevocable, although the Iranian government
would not take actions against Rushdie.
</P>
<P>
The statement condemned the British daily for "distorting"
Mohajerani's remarks, saying "this new ploy has long been rejected
by Iranian and even European public opinions."
</P>
<P>
"Considering Iran's unambiguous stance on the issue, a written
guarantee in this regard has long been out of the question," the
statement added.
</P>
<P>
Khomeini issued a religious order against Rushdie's life in
1989 after deeming the author's novel blasphemous to Islam. The
British writer has been forced to live under heavy protection of
the British police.
</P>
<P>
Rushdie's issue has been one of the most sticking problems
hampering the development of relations between Iran and the
European countries.
</P>
<P>
According to Iranian press, Mohajerani, during his interview
with the Independent, hoped Iran and the European Union (EU) would
restart negotiations on the death sentence on Rushdie following
the end of their diplomatic row last month.
</P>
<P>
The EU states had recalled their envoys from Tehran in protest
after a Berlin Court in April accused Iranian leadership of
involvement in the murder of two dissidents and sponsoring "state
terrorism." 
</P>
</TEXT>
