<HEADLINE> Over 35 Million Ethiopians Risk Iodine Deficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Over 35 million
Ethiopians, about 60 percent of the population, are at risk of
iodine deficiency diseases, the Ethiopian News Agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Quoting statistics from the Ethiopian Ministry of Health, the
report said some 26 persons in every 100 people in Ethiopia will
be found to have goitre.
</P>
<P>
About 50,000 pre-natal deaths are caused by severe iodine
deficiency in pregnant women annually, said the report.
</P>
<P>
As Ethiopia's environment is iodine poor, correction has to be
achieved through iodine supplementation. Ethiopia has cooperated
with the government of Eritrea, with the assistance from the
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), to ensure that all salt
coming in from Eritrea is iodine at the souse.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is strengthening community based monitoring
systems to ensure availability of iodized salt at the consumer
levels, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
