<HEADLINE> Mideast Peace Process near Dead End: Moussa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa warned today that the Mideast peace process is grinding to
a "dead end," the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Moussa made the remark after submitting a report to President
Hosni Mubarak on the results of the eighth Islamic summit held in
Iran on December 9-11 as well as the results of his recent
European tour of Germany and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that "The statements by Israeli Premier
Benjamin Netanyahu on regarding the West Bank as part of Israel
are considered, if true, a major setback."
</P>
<P>
On if Netanyahu's statements had driven the peace process to a
dead end, Moussa said that "the dead end was very close."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian territories in the West Bank and Gaza are occupied
lands and the U.N. Resolution 242 prohibits the acquisition of
land by force, the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa also noted that Palestinian National Authority President
Yasser Arafat, who is in Cairo for a two-day visit, said today
that there is no breakthrough in the peace march because of the
Israeli intransigent stance.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations have broken down
since March over the Israeli settlement building in East Jerusalem
and long overdue troop pullout from the occupied West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The recent U.S. bid to reactivate the peace process failed to
fix the time and scope of the Israeli further redeployment in the
West Bank. As a result, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
said that she will propose to President Bill Clinton to meet with
Arafat and Netanyahu in Washington in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
