<HEADLINE> Chinese, Syrian FMs Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen held talks here this evening with his
Syrian counterpart Farouq al-Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
The talks dealt with the international situation, ways of
establishing a just and comprehensive peace in the Middle East and
Sino-Syrian relations.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the Chinese foreign minister reaffirmed his
country's principled position on the Middle East peace process,
expressing China's readiness to contribute to pushing forward this
drive.
</P>
<P>
Qian also reiterated China's support for the restoration of
Syria's occupied Golan Heights and for Syria's demand that peace
negotiations with Israel should resume from where they were left
off.
</P>
<P>
On his part, the Syrian foreign minister welcomed Qian's visit
to Syria and outlined the present situation in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Middle East peace process is utterly
deadlocked due to the anti-peace policies adopted by the Israeli
government. He urged Israel to abide by relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Qian arrived here this afternoon from Beirut for a two-day
official visit to Syria, the second leg of his Middle East
tour. He will also visit Israel, the Palestinian self-rule areas
and Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
