<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some Shanghai People Prefer Having Ashes Scattered Into Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The ashes of 878 Shanghai
people were scattered out to sea this year after they were
cremated as they had chosen, and this was the largest number for
any area in China.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, which is the economic, financial and cultural center
of the country, is also taking a lead in changing funeral
practices. The cremation rate of the local residents has been
about 100 percent since the early 1960s, but the number of methods
of interment of ashes has grown, and that includes burial at grave
sites, being put in mausoleums, and being buried under a tree.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, Shanghai has had 23 collective funeral services at
sea, six of them this year, and the number of people has increased
three-fold since 1991.
</P>
<P>
"I think the scattering of Deng Xiaoping's ashes into the sea
has set a good example for our people," said Yu Kangwei, head of
the city's funeral and interment administration.
</P>
<P>
The scattering of ashes will be advertised and encouraged,
according to the Shanghai City Funeral and Interment Management
Regulations, which will go into effect on January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the scattering of ashes among nature may
become a very popular choice of Shanghai people in future, when
they die. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
