<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Says Northern City Should Be Modern Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng, during a
two-day visit to the northern city of Tianjin, told the local
government that they should work harder to build it into a
modernized port city and economic center.
</P>
<P>
The city is a municipality under the direct jurisdiction of the
central government, on the Bohai Sea.
</P>
<P>
It needs an industrial development plan, based solidly on the
city's actual conditions and should play a larger role in the
regional and national economy, Li said.
</P>
<P>
In the last five years, the city has maintained double-digit
growth in its GDP and low inflation, and the highest GDP, incomes,
gross industrial output, and foreign investment for any coastal
city in northern China.
</P>
<P>
The coastal area of Tianjin must concentrate on new technology
and marketable products, Li said, pointing out that the country's
markets are undergoing great changes in supply and demand for many
products, with supply sometimes exceeding demand, causing
difficulties for rural and township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin needs to improve management and technology in township
enterprises to make sure they can survive market competition, he
said.
</P>
<P>
In the company of State Councillor Luo Gan and Tianjin's Mayor
Zhang Lichang, Li visited the new Beiping-Tianjin Campaign Museum,
a museum for Zhou Enlai and his wife Deng Yingchao, which is under
construction, the city's container port, the Tianjin Economic and
Technological Development Zone, and the bonded zone.
</P>
<P>
Li and his wife Zhu Lin donated 1,000 yuan to the museum for
Zhou Enlai and Deng Yingchao.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Lin also donated a handbag used by Deng Yingchao that was
later given to her. 
</P>
</TEXT>
