<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1400 GMT, December 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral said
Sunday that the biggest challenge facing the country is to
convert "coalition reality into a coalition culture."
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of workers of Janata Dal, the main
constituent of the 14-party United Front, in Pune city of
southeastern India, Gujral said, "coalition is a political reality
 and the task is how to build a coalition culture. A single party
rule in the country is not possible." (India-PM-Coalition)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- The Civil Aviation Authority of Singapore (CAAS)
said Sunday that chances of finding any survivors from the
SilkAir MI185 crash near Palembang, Indonesia, are now remote.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that the CAAS made such an announcement
since search and rescue operation started last Friday night, hours
 after the Boeing 737-300 went down with 94 passengers and seven
crew on board. (Singapore-Air Crash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- The Vietnamese government will take steps to boost its
labor export, the Vietnam News Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Ministry of Labor, War Invalids and Social Affairs
has been directed to draft a labor export plan to the year 2000,
emphasizing the practical steps needed to boost labor exports, the
news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam considered labor export as an important step to solve
its problem of unemployment, the report said. (Vietnam-Labor
Export)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- The Thai Senate has approved the bankruptcy bill,
which will give debtors more room to re-arrange their debts with
creditors for business rehabilitation,
 instead of an immediate shutdown. (Thailand-Senate-Bankruptcy
Bill)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Striking U.S. pilots reached a tentative contract
agreement with Skyway Airlines today soon after they stopped work.
</P>
<P>
The strike by 135 pilots for the Midwestern airline started at
4:05 a.m. (1005 GMT) for higher wages. As the two sides reached an
agreement on the contract, the pilots returned to work at about
5:30 a.m. But it was not clear what the detail of the agreement
was. (US-Pilot-Strike) 
</P>
