<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC States Urged to Take New Policy towards Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 21 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian daily today urged
the ongoing summit of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) to adopt
a new policy towards Iran, which has made a series of goodwill
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
Tehran Times, which is believed to have good connection with
the Foreign Ministry, said the GCC states must prepare ground for
closer ties with Iran in all fields in the new atmosphere,
particularly after the eighth Islamic summit held in Tehran on
December 9-11.
</P>
<P>
"Iran has already suggested that it is ready to sign a
non-aggression pact with its Arab neighbors," it said, now the
ball is in the court of the GCC.
</P>
<P>
The daily stated that Iran also hopes that the GCC states
adopt a new approach to the "misunderstandings" between Iran and
the United Arab Emirates (UAE) over the disputed islands in the
Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Both Tehran and Abu Dhabi claimed full sovereignty over the
islands of Abu Musa, the greater and the lesser Tumbs despite
their agreement to co-rule them following the British withdrawal
from the region in 1971.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami has said that Iran is ready
to settle the issue with the UAE through negotiations at any
level, the paper said, the GCC should advise the UAE to respond.
</P>
<P>
The Khatami government has taken a series of steps to show
Tehran's goodwill for friendly relations and cooperation with the
Gulf sheikdoms, and Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi made a
week-long tour of the six states in November.
</P>
<P>
Tehran Times called on the GCC members to work for unity among
Muslim countries, saying it is not possible for the Muslims to
play an effective role in the world unless they first remove
differences among themselves.
</P>
<P>
The paper said GCC members have had a "successful gathering" at
the Islamic summit, and now the GCC summit is an appropriate
forum to close ranks among a limited number of Muslim countries,
paving the way for a broader cooperation among Muslims.
</P>
<P>
The GCC summit was opened in Kuwait Saturday, which showed
willingness to improve ties with Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
