<HEADLINE> Trade Unions In China's Non-State Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 21 (Xinhua) -- In China's non-state sector,
there are now about 153,000 trade unions in overseas-funded,
private, and rural businesses.
</P>
<P>
Trade unions in those so-called "new economic organizations"
covered 14.67 million workers by the end of September this year,
said Yang Xingfu, vice-chairman of the All China Federation of
Trade Unions (ACFTU), at a conference in Shanghai today. These
types of businesses employ 113.6 million in all.
</P>
<P>
Yang said that these new organizations still have a lot of
problems, with their more complicated labor relations, and some
have seriously infringed upon employees' rights and interests, so
establishing trade unions in these business is an urgent matter
for stable and harmonious labor relations, because they safeguard
workers' rights and interests and promote the healthy development.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one provinces have formulated regulations for trade
unions in overseas-funded businesses, Yang said, and a negotiation
and contract system has been set up in 17,789 overseas-funded
businesses, 6,085 private ones, and 15,396 rural ones.
</P>
<P>
The chairmen of trade unions in 8,865 overseas-funded
businesses are members of the board of directors or attend board
meetings as non-voting members.  
</P>
</TEXT>
