<HEADLINE> Dominant Chinese Miss One Title at ITTF Pro-Tour GF in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Dominant Chinese had only
one out of the four titles eluded off their fingers as Vladimir
Samsonov from Belarus took the men's singles crown at the 1997
International Table Tennis Federation Pro-Tour Grand Finals which
closed here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Samsonov, world championships runner-up this year and runner-up
at last year's Grand Finals, beat Chinese teenager sensation Wang
Liqin 21-16, 21-14, 14-21, 21-17 in the final Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Samsonov had won over Wang three times and lost once in their
four previous meetings.
</P>
<P>
Chinese swept all the four titles at last year's inaugural ITTF
Pro-Tour Grand Finals back in the northern Chinese city of Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
"I'm happy to win (the title) and, with this trophy, it came
out a perfect year for me," said Samsonov after his victory.
</P>
<P>
"Wang did quite well for some points today. As he is so young
and promising, he can surely do much better in the future," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"I'm a bit nervous and too anxcious to win today," an obviously
disappointed Wang said after the title clash.
</P>
<P>
China's head coach Cai Zhenhua had predicted before the final
that a lack of international experience set a gloomy background
for the Chinese teenager while good receiving would play a key
role if he was to win.
</P>
<P>
But Cai said he felt happy with his players, "considering that
they had been so tired after so heavy a schedule for this year and
that they had come into the Grand Finals here in under-par shape."
</P>
<P>
China's world number two Li Ju won over compatriot Wang Nan
three games to one to take the women's singles title Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Chinese also won the doubles titles on Sunday, with Kong
Linghui and Liu Guoliang in the men's and Li Ju and Wang Nan in
the women's.
</P>
<P>
World number two and top seed Li Ju beat world championships
runner-up and world number three Wang Nan 23-25, 21-5, 21-16,
21-17 in an all-Chinese women's singles final Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
World men's doubles champions Kong Linhui and Liu Guoliang from
China had to struggle from behind in the fourth game before
beating last year's runners-up, Jorg Rosskopf of Germany and
Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus 18-21, 21-16, 21-12, 21-19 to take
the title.
</P>
<P>
And the women's double title went to China's world runners-up
Li Ju and Wang Nan, who downed South Koreans Park Hae Jung and Kim
Moo Kyu 21-17, 21-13, 19-21, 21-13 in the final Sunday afternoon.
</P>
