will pay an official visit to Kenya as early as March or April if
his Kenyan counterpart Daniel arap Moi wins the coming poll, the
independent East African Standard newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department told the newspaper's reporter John
Knight who works in Los Angeles, that Nairobi will be the first
destination of Clinton's African tour scheduled for the first
half of 1998, said the report.
</P>
<P>
However, if Moi fails to win, "everything may have to be
re-assessed. Who can say?" Knight quoted a senior spokesman in
the U.S. State Department as saying.
</P>
<P>
The incumbent Kenyan President, who is widely expected to win
another five-year term in the December 29 poll, is regarded as
one of the United States' most reliable friends in Africa and a
world class statesman with whom business can be done, the report
claimed.
</P>
<P>
No details of the Clinton visit will be announced until after
the election.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright paid her visit to
seven countries in Africa on December 9-15 to pave the way for
President Clinton's tour of Africa next year and also to try to
establish "real partnership" with African countries.
</P>
<P>
Kenya, which is to hold general elections soon, was not
included in the trip of Albright. 
</P>
