<HEADLINE> India's Inflation Rises to 4.07 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 21 (Xinhua) -- India's annual rate of
inflation increased by 0.11 percentage points to cross the
four-percent mark to touch 4.07 for the week ended on December 6,
Press Trust of India (PTI) said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The inflation, based on wholesale price index, rose to 4.07
percent from 3.96 percent in the previous week but much lower than
the 7.15 percent for the corresponding week last year.
</P>
<P>
The index for "all commodities" also rose by 1.4 percent during
the week to 332.4 (provisional) as against 331.0 (provisional) for
the previous week. The final index for "all commodities" for the
week stood at 331.9 as against 330.7 in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
Economists have been suggesting an upturn in inflation because
of the increase in money supply in the second half of the current
fiscal year (April 1,1997-March 31, 1998). Leading economists said
that the low level of inflation was mainly due to slackening of
demand in the economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
