<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Island Province Puts Priority on Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, December 21 (Xinhua) -- South China's island province
of Hainan has placed top priority on environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
As one of China's less-polluted areas, the island province will
try to avoid the "treatment after pollution" path and give equal
priority to economic development and environmental protection, a
local government official said.
</P>
<P>
Hainan, one of China's five special economic zones, has passed
more than 20 laws and sets of regulations concerning the
environment and resources protection since it became a province in
1988. Nineteen cities and counties in the province have also
passed more than 60 sets of local regulations and rules to ensure
sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the province has invested nearly 100
million yuan on pollution clean-ups at hundreds of enterprises.
The discharge of wastes -- gas, water and solids -- per unit of
gross domestic product (GDP) is lower than the national average.
</P>
<P>
Hainan has closed 75 small factories that were polluters to
eliminate 5,600 tons of waste water, 18 million cubic meters of
waste gas, and 84 million tons of solid waste.
</P>
<P>
The province has 1.7 million hectares of forests, with green
coverage accounting for 50.2 percent, which includes 866,000
hectares of tropical virgin forests considered among the best in
the world.
</P>
<P>
The province, the biggest special economic zone in China, has
been listed by the State Council as one of the 12 key
environmental protection areas during the 1996-2010 period.
</P>
<P>
Hainan annually attracts millions of tourists, both domestic
and overseas, and the province has invested 6 billion U.S. dollars
and made use of more than 30 billion yuan of domestic funds in the
past nine years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
