<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecological Farming on Waste Mountains Used to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Qianxi County in north
China's Hebei Province is learning to maximize the productivity of
its rugged mountain areas while developing ecologically sound
farming.
</P>
<P>
Located in the mountainous region of the province, harsh
geographical conditions are a major barrier to local economic
growth. The per-capita arable land in the county was less than
0.066 hectares before the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987, people in the area have been transforming mountains
into terraced fields, where Chinese chestnuts and grain have been
intercropped.
</P>
<P>
At the foot of the mountains, Qianxi farmers have combined
apple and pear trees with grains. They have also planted pine and
scholar trees on the top of the mountains to further conserve
water and soil.
</P>
<P>
This "Mountain Enclosure Project," so named by local farmers,
has attracted 50 million yuan (six million U.S. dollars) in
investments.
</P>
<P>
The project has added 12,000 hectares of farmland and upgraded
6,000 hectares of low-yield fields. The mountain farming has
enhanced the county's annual grain capacity by seven million
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
It has also benefited the local ecology. Now, sideline products
from forestry, animal husbandry and aquatic breeding account for
66.8 percent of the total agricultural output, as opposed to 52.9
percent before the program was launched.
</P>
<P>
As the project widened its scope, such modern management
procedures as contracts and share-holding have been introduced to
define separate responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the county plans to encourage farmers to reclaim
remote mountain areas by auctioning. Farmers will have 30-to-50
years of rights to use the farmland they explore, during which
time taxes will be exempted up to a certain amount. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
