<HEADLINE> S'pore Authority Says Chances of Finding Air Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Civil Aviation Authority
of Singapore (CAAS) said Sunday that chances of finding any
survivors from the SilkAir MI185 crash near Palembang, Indonesia,
are now remote.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that the CAAS made such an announcement
since search and rescue operation started last Friday night, hours
after the Boeing 737-300 went down with 94 passengers and seven
crew on board.
</P>
<P>
The CAAS also confirmed at a press conference Sunday afternoon
that while three large parts of the wreckage have been recovered,
none of the main parts of the aircraft were found so far.
</P>
<P>
This confirmation was made in response to earlier news reports
here that the fuselage was found with trapped bodies inside.
</P>
<P>
Earlier a senior SilkAir public affairs official said that the
Boeing 737-300 that crashed had "not a single defect".
</P>
<P>
He said that the ten months old aircraft, leased from General
Electric Capital Auto Financial Services Inc. on February 14, this
year, underwent three checks called equalization checks.
</P>
<P>
These checks were said to be done every 100 flying hours as
recommended by the aircraft manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
These checks took about two days each time to complete and once
completed, the documentation has to be approved by the CAAS, he
said, adding that even the most minor defect was recorded and this
aircraft had not a single defect.
</P>
<P>
The last check for the aircraft was done on December 9, only
ten days before it crashed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
