<HEADLINE> China's First National Data System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- China will spend about 10
million US dollars on a national data network next year for the
domestic telecommunications market.
</P>
<P>
The US's Lucent Technologies announced today that it has signed
a contract with the Telecommunications Directorate under the
Chinese Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications to build the data
network based on the cellular digital packet data (CDPD)
technology.
</P>
<P>
The company will use the CDPD system for the ministry's data
network, China Radio Data Network. It has mobile data intermediate
systems in Beijing, Shanghai, and Guangzhou, and will go into
operation in six cities in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The CDPD can make people's day-to-day lives more convenient by
adding mobility to virtually any business that has a mobile work
force, according to Douglas Kirkpatrick, vice president of Lucent
Technologies (China) Company's network wireless systems division,
and the CDPD technology may allow the volume of data transmitted
over wireless networks to exceed the amount of voice traffic.
</P>
<P>
He says that users can obtain any data they want at any place
that has access to CDPD service, which is expected to be available
in most Chinese cities in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Lucent has six joint ventures and two wholely-owned companies
in China.  
</P>
