<HEADLINE> Indian Prime Minister on Coalition Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral said Sunday that the biggest challenge before the
country is to convert "coalition reality into a coalition
culture."
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of workers of Janata Dal, the main
constituent of the 14-party United Front, in Pune city of
southeastern India, Gujral said, "coalition is a political reality
and the task is how to build a coalition culture. A single party
rule in the country is not possible."
</P>
<P>
He further said that in a single party government the leader
would speak and others would follow. But in a coalition
government, a matter was debated for almost 15 hours before
arriving at a decision. "Coalition and consensus are two sides of
the same coin," he added.
</P>
<P>
"During our coalition experiment, although the cabinet was
attended by 14 parties forming the United Front, there was not a
single occasion when the decision was not taken unanimously,
despite earlier differences," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
