<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Continues to Discuss Redeployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli cabinet began
another session this morning to discuss its troop redeployment in
the West Bank, according to the Prime Minister's Office.
</P>
<P>
At today's session, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is to
brief the cabinet on his last Thursday's meeting with
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in Paris, in which the
two reportedly focused their attention on the linkage between
further Israeli redeployment and security guarantees from the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
The session will also provide another opportunity to close the
gaps between various ministers' assessments of the amount of
territory Israel can afford to transfer to the PNA's control, the
office said.
</P>
<P>
But "it will take more time, probably until January 15 next
year, for them to reach a consensus," it added.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu first proposed Israeli troop redeployment in the
West Bank at the end of November, but till now the Israeli
cabinet could not reach its final decision on how many territory
Israel could hand over to the PNA in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon suggested Israel
would have a 20 kilometer wide security zone in the Jordan River
Valley and another seven-to-10 kilometer wide security zone along
the 1949 Armistice Line on the western side of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Besides that, he also suggested to build several
Israeli-controlled "strategic roads" to cut the West Bank into
blocs.
</P>
<P>
Under Sharon's plan, Israel would still control about 70
percent of the West Bank in the final settlement.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu, together with Foreign Minister David Levy, was
reported to favor the plan proposed by Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai, who recommended narrowing the width of the two planned
security zones to three to six kilometers and seven to 10
kilometers respectively.
</P>
<P>
Under Mordechai's proposal, Israel will retain control over
50-55 percent of the territories in the final settlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
