<HEADLINE> North China City Protects Laborers' Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Local authorities in Tianjin,
a major port city in north China, have stepped up efforts to
protect the rights of laborers by helping them recover delayed
salaries and other financial losses.
</P>
<P>
So far, 62 local work units that have violated relevant laws
and regulations in delaying the payment to their laborers
according to law have been punished, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin has issued or revised 12 local laws to protect the
rights of local laborers, and 598 local people have been appointed
as full-time or part-time labor supervisors.
</P>
<P>
This year, local authorities have inspected salary and pension
records, the distribution of money to needy families, the
employment of laborers in private enterprises, and unemployment
funds.
</P>
<P>
During the check-up, 59 unlawful job agencies were canceled and
19 under-age laborers dismissed. In the meantime, 38,700 people
who did not sign their work contract with the employers have been
asked to do so.
</P>
<P>
A total of 650,000 yuan illegally collected by some work units
from their employees as "honest money" has been paid back to
laborers, while 2.35 million yuan of salaries due have been paid
to employees.
</P>
<P>
By the end of October, 5,490 work units had been inspected,
while officials had received 2,145 calls, letters and visits by
people reporting law-breakers. A total of 683 cases have been
investigated.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971221.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Insists on S. Leone Junta's Quit on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- West African countries have
reaffirmed their steadfast demand that the military junta in
Sierra Leone return power to ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah
on April 22 next year as agreed.
</P>
<P>
The restatement, made by the ECOWAS committee of five on
Sierra Leone in Abuja Saturday, followed the threat from the
junta leader Major Johnny Paul Koroma to delay the hand-over.
</P>
<P>
Koroma said Friday that he was unlikely to honor the hand-over
deadline in view of delay in disarming combatants in the
embattled country.
</P>
<P>
Koroma's warning met with strong opposition from the
committee, set up by the Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS) to coordinate the restoration of the legitmate
government of Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting in the capital of Nigeria Saturday, the committee
stressed the need to adhere strictly to the time table of the
Conakry peace accord which fixes both the date of hand-over and
disarmament, among other things.
</P>
<P>
According to a 16-point communique issued at the end of the
meeting, the ECOWAS-brokered peace plan remains the best
framework for the restoration of peace and constitutional order
in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Noting that there had been some violations of the ECOWAS and
United Nations sanctions imposed on the junta, the committee
called for strict adherance to the sanction.
</P>
<P>
The committee, comprising foreign ministers of Nigeria, Ghana,
Guinea, Cote d'Ivoire and Liberia, called on those harboring
members of the military junta, their families and all others on
the restricted list to repartriate such persons to Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
It mandated the ECOWAS peace-keeping force known as Ecomog to
close the airstrip at Mabguraka recently upgraded to a
full-fledged airport by the junta.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, the illegal regime is using the
airport for the importation of arms and other supplies in
violation of the sanctions and embargo against it.
</P>
<P>
The committee urged the U.N. Security Council to accelerat
efforts aimed at deploying a U.N. military observer's mission to
Sierra Leone and called on member states to contribute urgently
more troops to enhance the Ecomog operational capacity in that
country.
</P>
<P>
Deploring the incessant and unprovoked attacks on Ecomog
forces, the committee reaffirmed the right Ecomog forces to
defend themselves.
</P>
<P>
On the notice of the Liberia's government's notice to the
11,000-strong Ecomog to leave the country by February 2 next
year, the committee said Ecomog's departure would have
implications for the implementation on the ECOWAS peace plan in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, a follow-up of the ECOWAS extraordinary summit in
Lome last Friday, was also attended by the ECOWAS Executive
Secretary, representatives of the Organization of African Unity
and observers from Sierra Leone as well as the U.N.
Secretary-General's special envoy to that troubled country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
