<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Company to Build Refinery in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- A Malaysian oil company has
agreed to build an oil refinery unit in Bangladesh to help the
South Asian country out of dependence on imported petroleum
products, a local newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Malaysia's state-run oil giant, Petronas,
negotiated in Dhaka last week with Bangladesh Petroleum
Corporation (BPC)
on installing a second unit of the Eastern Refinery, the sole
crude-refining plant in the country, the Independent daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
"They have agreed to raise the refining capacity of the Eastern
Refinery," BPC Chairman Fazlul Huq was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The current unit of the refinery, in the port city of
Chittagong, southeast Bangladesh, has a refining capacity of
31,000 barrels per day, which can only meet 40 percent of the
country's total demand for refined petroleum products of 3 million
metric tons a year.
</P>
<P>
The second unit of the refinery would have a capacity of 60,000
to 100,000 barrels per day, and would cost 300 million U.S.
dollars, according to Huq.
</P>
<P>
The total oil demand of the country will reach 4.5 million
metric tons in 2001 when the new refinery unit is expected to be
completed, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
