<HEADLINE> HK Tourist Arrivals Down 22 percent in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals in Hong
Kong totaled just 792,800 in November, down 22 percent from a year
ago, local press reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The continued slump was led by a plunge in most Asian markets
which were plagued by financial hardships, said the Hong Kong
Tourist Association (HKTA).
</P>
<P>
The association's figures showed that Hong Kong's top and third
largest markets, Japan and Taiwan, dropped by 59.3 percent and
16.6 percent respectively while the decline in South and Southeast
Asia was 24.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
But tourists from Hong Kong's second largest market, the
China's inland areas, edged up 1.8 percent over a year ago to
reach 200,000. Long-haul markets, including America, Australia
and New Zealand, also recorded slight increases.
</P>
<P>
In the first 11 months of this year, tourist arrivals totaled
9.6 million in Hong Kong, down 9.4 percent from the same period of
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
