<HEADLINE> Lebanon Expects 1998 Better Year for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Information Minister
Bassem Al-Sabaa today voiced hope that his country would be able
to "make a leap" on the road to achieve regional peace in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In an interview this morning with the Egyptian Voice of Arabs
radio over telephone from Beirut, Sabaa said that realization of
any peace in the region should hinge on full liberalization of
lands from Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese official is also critical of America's lack of
effectiveness in its current mediation between the Arabs and
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. role in the Mideast peace process at present reflects
a desire to push forward talks on all tracks but until now there
is no sign of translating this desire (into action)," he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, whose latest bid to
reactivate the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks has floundered,
said she expected 1998 will hold out better prospects for the
Mideast peace-making.
</P>
<P>
Sabaa said Israel's repeated attacks on south Lebanon are out
of its wish to make Lebanon "a scene for domestic and regional
problems."
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops have been launching strikes from the
1,200-square-kilometer "security zone" in south Lebanon it carved
out in 1985 to protect its northern territories from cross-border
guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks on the Syrian and Lebanese tracks have shown no
sign of a possible resumption since stalled in February 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
