<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Boost Labor Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government will
take steps to boost its labor export, the Vietnam News Agency
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Ministry of Labor, War Invalids and Social Affairs
has been directed to draft a labor export plan to the year 2000,
emphasizing the practical steps needed to boost labor exports, the
news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam considered labor export as an important step to solve
its problem of unemployment, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the new plan, the government will open the labor
market, allowing non-state economic sectors to engage in labor
export.
</P>
<P>
The policies will broaden and diversify job training and
foreign language teaching, develop more foreign labor outlets,
create conditions for Vietnamese workers to have access to job
training abroad, and allow workers to do several jobs.
</P>
<P>
The government will also trim back the administrative
procedures for labor export businesses and reduce the rate of
fees required for the export of labor or even exempt poor people
from such fees.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam exported 12,661 workers in 1996, some 15.6 times more
than the figure in 1992, which was the first year of the new labor
export mechanism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
