<DOCNO> XIE19971221.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: OPEC to Produce More, Earn Less </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) is expected to produce more
oil but earn less money in 1998 due to a widely believed
considerable decline in world oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Last month, OPEC decided to increase its oil output by 10
percent in the coming new year to reach 27.5 million barrels per
day (bpd). However, the predicted decline in world oil prices
would make the increase not worth the candle.
</P>
<P>
Latest reports from world crude stocks showed that by the
middle of this month, Brent blend, the world's benchmark grade
loosened 20 percent to 17.1 U.S. dollars a barrel, the lowest in
the past 22 months compared with 22 dollars a barrel two months
ago.
</P>
<P>
The prices were also nearly 12 percent down from this
year's averaged 19.43 dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
A November report by the United Arab Emirates' (UAE) Strategic
Studies and Research Center predicted that OPEC's 10 members,
except Iraq, would lose at least 17.5 billion dollars in 1998 even
if prices could be luckily kept at the level of 17.5 dollars a
barrel.
</P>
<P>
The report by the UAE, one of OPEC's major members, estimated
OPEC countries' oil earning at some 169.02 billion dollars in
1997 while their oil production at some 24.1 million barrels bpd.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the report said, OPEC's oil exports (except Iraq's)
would be no more than 167.26 billion dollars despite the increased
output.
</P>
<P>
Many oil experts expected even lower figures. They said the
down trend in world oil prices, which was triggered by growing
oversupply and compounded by OPEC's decision to increase output
will accelerate next year.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Ali, marketing manager in UAE's Abu Dhabi National
Oil Company, said since OPEC considered to increase its total oil
output, world oil prices have began to go downhill when fears
grew that a flood of oil would swamp markets next spring and
summer.
</P>
<P>
He said figures from world crude stocks showed that from
October to November, world oil prices sharply declined from 22
dollars a barrel to some 18 dollars a barrel, the psychologically
important level for world oil prices.
</P>
<P>
OPEC drove the last nail for the plunge trend and made prices
hit the lowest 17.1 dollars a barrel after it decided in Jakarta,
Indonesia last month to put the new cap on its members' oil
production, a decision giving buyers more confidence to bet on
ample supply in the new year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, countries outside of OPEC are gearing up to produce
more catalyst for the oversupply next year.
</P>
<P>
An October report by the Petroleum Intelligence Weekly, an
authorized oil magazine, said though many oil field projects are
at risk or delay due to a shortage of oil rigs and other
technical supplies, non-OPEC countries could pump into world
markets 1.2 million to 1.4 million bpd of fresh oil next year.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has also been piling downward pressure on the markets in
recent days. Two weeks ago, Iraqi oil Minister Amir Mohammed
Rashid said he hoped to resume oil exports in a "few weeks" but
only after Iraq and the U.N. agree on a distribution plan for food
and medicine.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is currently allowed to sell 2 billion dollars worth of
oil every six months under the Iraqi-U.N. oil-for-food deal, which
enabled Iraq to get food and medicine for its people suffering
under the U.N.-imposed sanctions against its invasion of Kuwait in
1990.
</P>
<P>
There was the prospect of a jump in the amount of oil Iraq is
allowed to sell. Iraq sold just under 700,000 barrels per day in
the first year of the deal and the U.N. might increase the amount
next year to 3 billion or 4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Another bearish factor that threatens OPEC's 1998 oil economy
is the slackened world demand caused by a currency crisis
spreading in Asia since the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
London-based Petroleum Argues, another oil magazine, said in
its latest report that Asian demand is expected to be downgraded
by 340,000 barrels per day for next year and may end up being cut
more if China is sucked into the crisis.
</P>
<P>
But the full impact of Asia's financial crisis caused by the
devaluation of currencies in South Korea and Thailand on oil
consumption remains unclear and analysts said it could slice
deeper into oil demand.
</P>
<P>
The region accounts for a quarter of world oil demand and
over the past five years has contributed nearly 50 percent of
global growth in crude demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971221.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
