<HEADLINE> Mozambican Minister Denies Legalizing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Minister of the
Interior has denied that the government has legalized
prostitution in the country, local weekly "Domongo" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
He said Saturday prostitution has affected almost all
Mozambican cities and that the whole society should be
concerned over this issue.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that prostitution is a kind of crime,
noting that the police don't want to legalize prostitution and
what the police have done is aimed at cracking down on it.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the police in Maputo summoned 500 prostitutes to a
meeting and banned their presence at other areas except Bagamoyo
Road of the coastal business township of Baixa in the capital,
saying this will facilitate the police to protect them and their
customers from raids by criminals.
</P>
<P>
This move of the police was regarded by capital residents as
legalizing prostitution.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique declared prostitution as illegal after winning
independence in 1975. 
</P>
