<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera Kills 120 in Zanzibar, Poor Sanitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Poor sanitation,
manifested by lack of toilets and waste disposal pits, has been
cited as a leading cause for the outbreak of cholera in Zanzibar
which has claimed 120 lives in the past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
According to Sunday News today, World Health Organization
(WHO)'s Acting Country Representative in Tanzania, Mohammed Amri,
said here on Saturday that 70.3 percent of households in Unguja
and Pemba, major islands of Zanzibar, have no toilets.
</P>
<P>
More than 54 percent of the Zanzibar residents are drawing
unpiped water, and the rest use piped water which is inadequately
treated.
</P>
<P>
Amri said most of Zanzibar, including the historic stone town,
is too dirty with faecal elements in pools and other stagnant
water areas.
</P>
<P>
He said the municipal authorities also seemed incapable of
handling refuse collection and disposal.
</P>
<P>
In the last 48 hours, some 248 cholera patients were
discharged, and yesterday afternoon 203 patients were still
staying at the Mnazi Mmoja Hospital, the largest medical
institution in Zanzibar, and at the three treatment camps at
Rahaleo, Magogoni and Kivunge.
</P>
<P>
WHO officials have prompted people with minor symptoms to rush
to hospitals for medical check.
</P>
<P>
A WHO delegation is expected to arrive in Zanzibar as part of
United Nations' long-term support program to eradicate cholera in
the Zanzibar isles and the entire Lake Victoria region, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
Amri said Tanzania has recorded 32,000 cholera cases since
January this year, making it the worst hit country in Africa. The
continental figure is 64,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
