<HEADLINE> Southwest Chinese Port Plays Larger Role with New Railway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- With the completion of the
Nanning-Kunming Railway, China's southwestern trunk line,
Fangcheng Port in Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region has played a
more prominent role in the region's cargo trade.
</P>
<P>
The port is one of China's most important sea outlets to
Southeast Asia. Midwest provinces' foreign trade through the port
will save 2016 km in railway journey and 900 sea miles of
transport compared with that through the Shanghai Port, the
largest in China.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that in 1995, the port handled total
cargo worth 219 million yuan (26.3 million U.S. dollars)for
Yunnan, Guizhou and Sichuan provinces in the midwest
region. However, by the end of the first three quarters of this
year, the port has already had 1.14 billion yuan (137 million
dollars) worth of cargo transport.
</P>
<P>
Now, the import and export in the three provinces have
accounted for 28.2 percent of the port's total cargo transport, as
against 3.35 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Fangcheng Port owns nine berths, each capable of
accommodating 10,000-ton vessels, and has a combined capacity of
8.5 million tons annually. It reported six million tons of cargo
by the end of this November, compared with 5.08 million tons for
all of 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
