<HEADLINE> Sichuan to Green up Whole Province in 10 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Sichuan
Province plans to launch a massive ecological protection project
to deal with soil erosion and the destruction of vegetation, and
in particular, protect the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Part of the project will focus on the forestry areas in the
province, covering the Jinsha, Yalong, Minjiang and Dadu river
valleys in the upper reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Also, shelter forests will be planted in the Three Gorges
reservoir area to ensure the quality of water in the reservoir.
</P>
<P>
The project also includes protection of natural forests in the
source areas of the Yangtze River in a bid to protect biological
diversity and ensure water conservation of the forests there.
</P>
<P>
Over the past four decades, Sichuan has planted more than four
million hectares of forests, raising the forest coverage rate up
to 20.35 percent from nine percent in the early 1960s, said a
leading official from the provincial forestry department.
</P>
<P>
However, the deterioration of ecological environment continues,
he said. For that, Sichuan plans to spend the next ten years in
greening up the whole province and another two decades in setting
up a perfect ecological system across the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971221.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Contracted Taiwanese Investment Drops in Mainland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Contracted Taiwanese
investment in the mainland has dropped sharply, despite a slight
increase in actual investment, according to the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
A ministry official said that the total contracted Taiwanese
investment was 2.013 billion US dollars between January and
September, dropping by 54 percent over the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
From January to September, Chinese mainland approved 2,181
Taiwanese-invested projects, down 9.1 percent over the same period
of 1996, the official said.
</P>
<P>
However, Taiwanese investment actually used during the first
nine months reached 2.49 billion US dollars, increasing by 0.49
percent over last year's same period.
</P>
<P>
The official attributed the drop of contracted investment to
the Taiwanese authorities' present policy on trade and economic
ties across the Straits, which he said has deprived Taiwanese
entrepreneurs of business opportunities on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Also, the official said, the drop in contracted investment can
be attributed to the readjustment of taxation policy by the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that Taiwanese investment has flowed to
broader areas of business this year, with insurance, securities
and bank becoming new focuses, adding that more Taiwanese business
people have come to be interested in investing in agriculture and
high-technology.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the huge market on China's mainland
remains attractive to overseas investors and, "as the competition
is getting fierce, the early-comers can be quickly replaced by
their rivals if they hesitate."
</P>
<P>
By September this year, Taiwan has launched 37,652 projects on
the mainland all together, totaling 37.37 billion US dollars of
contracted investment, with 17.57 billion US dollars actually used.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months this year, Taiwan was the third
largest investor in the mainland in terms of actual investment,
next to Hong Kong and Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
