<HEADLINE> Tianjin Reaps Agricultural Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 21 (Xinhua) -- North China's coastal city of
Tianjin has achieved an agricultural harvest rarely seen in
history, with over 2 billion kg of grain to be reaped, despite
sever drought this year.
</P>
<P>
The city was afflicted with a severe drought this summer, with
the rainfall during the June-April period dropping to only 100-200
mm, down nearly 70 percent compared with normal years. The city's
more than 800 million cubic meters of rain water stored last year
helped to ease the drought, a local official said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, advanced technology was used in developing
agriculture, making it possible to transform over 200,000 mu
(13,333 hectares) of saline-alkali land and less productive field
in the Baodi County into fertile soil.
</P>
<P>
"This alone has added more than 50 million kg of grains to the
total output," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the city has planted more crops in the northern
regions where the drought was less serious, and has applied potash
fertilizer to one million mu of land, up 300,000 mu over last year.
</P>
<P>
Fine varieties of wheat, maize and rice have also been
introduced on an extensive basis, the official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971221.0108 </DOCNO>
