<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Smuggling Rampant in Southern Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Oil smuggling is rife in the
Andaman sea in southern Thailand following the depreciation of the
baht which has caused oil prices to soar on the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Increased oil smuggling has resulted from price gaps between
Thailand and Singapore, the Bangkok Post Sunday quotes a Thai navy
intelligence officer as saying.
</P>
<P>
Smuggled oil is brought from Singapore by tankers to a location
outside the Thai territorial waters in the Andaman sea. It is then
transported from the tankers by modified fishing boats for sale to
operators of fishing boats.
</P>
<P>
Cheaper smuggled oil helps fishermen reduce their operation
costs, said the intelligence officer, captain Pongsathorn
Kawekorn, deputy director of the Third Fleet's Intelligence
Division.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971221.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Andaman Sea States Pursue Stronger Transport Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The littoral countries of the
Andaman Sea have agreed to put priority on the development of
subregional transport network in a bid to forge ahead their
cooperation, a senior Thai Foreign Ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials from members of the BISTEC - a subregional
economic cooperation group embracing Bangladesh, India, Sri Lanka,
Thailand, and now Myanmar - stressed the importance of transport
and communications linkage in the subregional cooperation,
according to Kobsak Chutikul, head of the Economic Affairs
Department under the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The officials noted that lack of such links is a main obstacle
to cooperation among the countries along the Andaman sea rim,
Kobsak said on Saturday after a two-day meeting of senior
officials from the BISTEC here.
</P>
<P>
They have chosen to expedite some transport projects in the
subregion, including the Asian highway and the Trans-Asian
railway, to kick off their subregional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The BISTEC was formed at a meeting in June this year in Bangkok
with an aim to foster social and economic development in the
subregion through subregional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar expressed interest in joining the BISTEC in August and
it will formally be integrated into the non-binding group on
Monday when BISTEC ministerial-level officials meet here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971221.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Ministry to Readjust Health Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Ministry of Public
Health is reassessing the country's health and disease trends for
the coming years under a new economic situation.
</P>
<P>
The ministry had expected a booming economy and prepared for
the so-called rich people's diseases, such as obesity and heart
diseases.
</P>
<P>
However, with a general economic slump, the ministry has to
focus on more basic and common diseases, such as malnutrition and
communicable diseases.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the health sector also has to cope with increasing
cases of mental problems, like stress and depression, Dr.
Narongsak Angkhasuvaphala, deputy permanent secretary for the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, state hospitals need to prepare themselves for a
large increase of patients, as more people will switch from
expensive private hospitals to state ones for cheaper treatment.
</P>
<P>
He also urged state hospitals to reduce spending on expensive
medical equipment and avoid unnecessary distribution of drugs like
antibiotics, according to the Bangkok Post Sunday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
