<HEADLINE> Thailand to Receive Extra Yen Loans from Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Japan is expected to extend
additional yen loans worth up to 600 million U.S. dollars to
Thailand to support Thai exports, Thai Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanhaeminda said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The deal could be concluded in early next year to help ease
liquidity pressure on Thai exporters, Tarrin said after he
returned from a three-day trip to Japan.
</P>
<P>
The loans will be provided in credits by the Export-Import Bank
of Japan in conjunction with Thai commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Winning the loans was one of the achievements of Tarrin's
recent trip to Japan, local newspapers said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin made the trip to Japan with a main aim to persuade
Japanese institutions to roll over their loans granted to the Thai
private sector, which now bears foreign debts totaling 72 billion
dollars, over half of the amount owed to Japanese lenders.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin's trip also had another aim, which was to increase the
Japanese yen's role in trade and investment in Thailand, including
the conversion of outstanding dollar-denominated loans into yen
loans.
</P>
<P>
Swapping existing dollar loans for yen would reduce costs for
Thai borrowers as yen loans offer a lower interest rate, Tarrin
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
