<DOCNO> XIE19971221.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Travelers Change Preferences in Overseas Shopping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- For international travelers,
the luggage of Chinese might be among the biggest and the
heaviest. But the items in the luggage have greatly changed over
the years.
</P>
<P>
In the past, Beijing residents on business trips abroad used to
take back such jumbo goods as TV sets, refrigerators and, for the
least, microwave ovens.
</P>
<P>
However, according to a Beijing customs official quoted by
Beijing Youth Daily: "The age of Beijingers carrying TV sets and
refrigerators from abroad is over. What they bring home is
increasingly smaller and reflect the higher quality of their life."
</P>
<P>
The choice of goods varies according to the buyer's gender,
customs officials said. Women seem to prefer cosmetics and
nutritional supplements. They buy cosmetics not only for
themselves but also for their friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
Believing that calcium is good for their health, many women
travelers bring back supplements containing fish oil for their
parents and in-laws.
</P>
<P>
As for men, digital cameras, video equipment and notebook
computers are on the top of their shopping lists.
</P>
<P>
Beijing residents rarely buy clothes abroad nowadays, except
for leather. A man who works in the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation said he was foolish enough to buy China-made
suits in New York, but was pleased with the leather clothes he
purchased in Italy.
</P>
<P>
Some better-off Beijingers like to buy such articles as
tableware, kitchen utensils and ornaments, which they say are not
well-developed in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
