<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Police Uncover First Drug-Producing Mill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian police, in a recent
anti-drug operation, uncovered the country's first narcotic
drug-producing mill near the capital city and detained one
suspect, the local media reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
After an eight-month investigation, agents with the National
Anti-Organized Crime Agency raided the mill at the Opitsvet
Village, 15 kilometers away from Sofia, on December 20, seizing
300 kilograms of amphetamine and detaining the technician in
charge of organizing and supervising the production procedure.
</P>
<P>
The amphetamine seized is estimated to have a street value of
3.7 million U.S. dollars. Amphetamine is a drug used formerly in
medicine, but it is now used illegally by people wanting
excitement.
</P>
<P>
Covering a total area of 1.5 hectares, the mill is disguised as
a "chemical laboratory," and comprises three workshops with
up-to-date equipment.
</P>
<P>
The local media said that police are making efforts to hunt
down other suspects in the case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
