<HEADLINE> Czech-EU Trade Leaps to New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic's trade with
the European Union (EU) over the first 10 months of this year
amounted to 783.2 billion korunas (23 billion U.S. dollars), an
increase of 15.6 percent over the same period of last year, the
State Statistics Bureau said.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures released by the bureau showed that the
country's exports to the EU in this period soared to 351.3
billion korunas (10.3 billion dollars), a rise of 20.9 percent
over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Its imports from the bloc grew 11.7 percent to 431.9 billion
korunas (12.7 billion dollars), making a trade deficit of 80.6
billion korunas (2.4 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The EU has replaced the former Soviet Union as the leading
trading partner of the Czech Republic since 1990 when the country
began to adopt market economy.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, their trade was 817 billion korunas (24 billion
dollars), accounting for 61.3 percent of the country's total
foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
