<HEADLINE> Bank Holdups Increase in Sao Paulo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Bankers of San Paulo,
the southeastern Brazilian state, should be on the alert since the
state witnessed 13 percent more bank holdups and holdup attempts
in 1997, the local daily "Folha de Sao Paulo" reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Brazilian Bankers Syndicate, some 1,546 bank
holdups in the state were recorded up to October 1997. The number
is expected to reach 1,900 by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The increase of bank holdups should be mainly attributed to the
lack of investment in security systems of the banking
institutions, the newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
As the Brazilian Federation of Banking Associations estimated,
the 15,000 banking agencies set up in the country spend just one
billion reals (about 917 million U.S. dollars) each year in their
security systems. 
</P>
