<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EF Language Edges Clear in Race to Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- EF Language of Sweden had
increased her lead Sunday to almost 11 miles with 486 miles to the
finish in the third leg of the Whitbread Round The World race
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
At 5 a.m. (1800 GMT Saturday), EF Language was about 55 miles
past King Island on the western side of Bass Strait, which
separates the Australian mainland from Tasmania.
</P>
<P>
Swedish Match, the winner of the second leg from Cape Town to
Fremantle, was second and averaging the best boat speed of the
nine-strong fleet at 12.6 knots.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Silk Cut and Toshiba of the United States were the
marked improvers over the last 12 hours to 1800 GMT, gaining
almost eight miles on EF Language.
</P>
<P>
Both Silk Cut and Toshiba were taking a northerly course away
from the fleet. Although losing ground Saturday they had made up
the leeway overnight.
</P>
<P>
In fifth place was Norway's Innovation Kvaerner, around 14
miles behind the leader and averaging around 10 knots in the 15-20
knot north-westerly winds.
</P>
<P>
Chessie Racing, of the United States, another boat which lost
ground when the fleet compressed into Bass Strait, made up 5.7
miles on the leader overnight and was 19.5 miles from EF Language.
</P>
<P>
Monaco's Merit Cup and Sweden's EF Education had lost ground,
but Dutch yacht Brunel Sunergy had improved to seventh place, a
slight gain of 0.7 miles on the leader.
</P>
<P>
The leader is expected to cross the Sydney finish line sometime
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Positions at 1800 GMT (with distances from leader and from the
finish):
</P>
<P>
1. EF Language (0/486 miles)
</P>
<P>
2. Swedish Match (10.6m/496m)
</P>
<P>
3. Silk Cut (11.3m/497m)
</P>
<P>
4. Toshiba (13.6m/499m)
</P>
<P>
5. Innovation Kvaerner (14.1m/500m)
</P>
<P>
6. Chessie Racing (19.5m/505m)
</P>
<P>
7. Brunel Sunergy (22.2m/508m)
</P>
<P>
8. Merit Cup (25.7m/511m)
</P>
<P>
9. EF Education (26.3m/512m)
</P>
</TEXT>
