<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras Dominates with Young Generation Shining (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December xx (Xinhua) -- American legend Pete Sampras
still kept his domination in tennis court throughout the past
season, but the foundation of the sport beneath him has started to
shift.
</P>
<P>
The American, 26, is the only player who has captured two Grand
Slams in a single season -- Wimbledon and the Australian Open.
With his victory in the season-ending elite eight tournament,
Sampras has collected a total of eight titles.
</P>
<P>
His superority on any surface except clay in the French Open
earned him the name of the best player in the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
By finishing as No.1 on the ATP Tour rankings for the fifth
consecutive year, Sampras has tied the record of fellow American
Jimmy Conners in the 70's.
</P>
<P>
Since the inception of the ranking system in 1973, only 13
players have ever been No. 1 and only nine have ever finished the
year No. 1.
</P>
<P>
Sampras swapped the No. 1 ranking with Andre Agassi and Thomas
Muster early in 1996, but regained it on April 15 and has held it
since.
</P>
<P>
When Sampras was fighting to keep the position, Agassi was
making efforts in Challengers and Muster has dropped to No. 9 in
the rankings.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the season, there were few players who dominated and
many lower-ranked newcomers rose through the ranks by beating the
established stars and reaching the late stages of events and
winning titles.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Rafter, 24, was among them. He began the year ranked
No. 62, but went on to win the U.S. Open, his first major title.
The Australian has finished the year at No. 2.
</P>
<P>
Swede Jonas Bjorkman began the year ranked No. 69. After
winning his third title of the year in Stockholm on home soil,
Bjorkman has shot to No. 4 in the world.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year-old Swede also made a great achievement at the end
of the year, leading Sweden to beat the United States for the
Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
The Swede has one of the best returns in tennis. His
breakthrough has helped him shake off a reputation of being mainly
a successful doubles player.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Bjorkman had a 25-25 singles record. This year, he
leads the tour with more than 70 match wins.
</P>
<P>
"Jonas is a very talented player," Michael Chang once said.
"He is one of the few players who really has an all-court game."
</P>
<P>
"He has a good serve, good volleys and is very solid off the
ground," Chang said.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Moya, the Australian Open finalist from Spain, has been
the youngest player moving into the ATP Tour Championships. Moya,
21, has finished the year at No. 7.
</P>
<P>
American Michael Chang, who dropped to No. 3 after the ATP Tour
Championships in November, has another solid year with five
tournament wins.
</P>
<P>
Yvegeni Kafelnikov of Russia jumped to finish the year at No. 5
after beating Czech Petr Korda to claim the Kremlin Cup.
</P>
<P>
Gustavo Kuerten, from Brazil, failed to win any tournament
after taking the French Open. He finished the year at No. 14.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971221.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras Dominates with Young Generation Shining (2-last) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In women's tennis, young generation stole the limelight and
only Jana Novotna struck a blow for the older ones.
</P>
<P>
Without any doubt, the year should belong to Swiss sensation
Martina Hingis, who claimed her third Grand Slam title of the year
at the U.S. Open before her 17th birthday.
</P>
<P>
The world number one finished the year with 12 singles titles
-- twice as many as Lindsay Davenport who was second with six --
and earned a record of nearly 3.5 million U.S. dollars in prize
money.
</P>
<P>
The one Grand Slam title to elude Hingis this year was claimed
by Croatian Iva Majoli, who was 19 at the time.
</P>
<P>
And Charismatic teen-agers like U.S. Open runner-up Venus
Williams, Croatian newcomer Mirjana Lucic and Russian Ana
Kournikova all grabbed a share of spotlight in 1997 and all are
strong challengers for Hingis in years to come.
</P>
<P>
Novotna, at the advanced age of 29, concluded the year at world
No. 2 with the biggest title of her career in the Chase
Championships.
</P>
<P>
The Czech player, whose greatest liability has always been
mental, will take soaring confidence into the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
And next year, another old timer by the name of Steffi Graf,
28, will be recovered from the knee surgery that took her out of
the picture much of the year. The German superstar, who missed
both Wimbledon and the U.S. Open, will be back in time to
challenge Hingis at the Australian Open in January.
</P>
<P>
In early November, WTA tour players Linda Harvey Wilde of the
United States, Karin Kschwendt of Luxembourg and Patricia Hy
Boulais of Canada spearheaded a revolt at the Chicago tournament
aimed at improving the stature of rank-and-file players.
</P>
<P>
The WTA Tour has received a temporary restraining court order
against the move, in which three members were removed from the
player association's executive board and replaced by associates
sympathetic to mid-ranked players' objectives.
</P>
<P>
In the next season, women's tennis circuit will add six new
lower level tournaments and increase prize money.
</P>
<P>
Winners of four Grand Slams:
</P>
<P>
Australian Open:
</P>
<P>
Men's Singles: Pete Sampras, United States
</P>
<P>
Women's Singles: Martina Hingis, Switzerland
</P>
<P>
French Open:
</P>
<P>
Men's Singles: Gustavo Kuerten, Brazil
</P>
<P>
Women's Singles: Iva Majoli, Croatia
</P>
<P>
Wimbledon:
</P>
<P>
Men's Singles: Pete Sampras, United States
</P>
<P>
Women's Singles: Martina Hingis, Switzerland
</P>
<P>
U.S. Open:
</P>
<P>
Men's Singles: Patrick Rafter, Australia
</P>
<P>
Women's Singles: Martina Hingis, Switzerland
</P>
<P>
ATP Tour Championships winner: Pete Sampras, United States
</P>
<P>
Chase Championships winner: Jana Novotna, Czech Republic
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
