<HEADLINE>    BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major Beijing-based newspapers: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- The paper frontpages a commentary calling on officials at
all levels to take lead in studying the principles, policies and
tasks set at the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of
China, and in carrying on the Party's fine traditions of serving,
listening to and relying on the people, so as to ensure progress
of work in all spheres.
</P>
<P>
-- As the two year countdown of Macao's return to China was
observed Saturday, local personalities urged residents to unite
and work towards a better future of Macao.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC),
returned to Beijing yesterday aftering winding up his official
goodwill visit to Viet Nam, New Zealand and Australia.
</P>
<P>
-- Fifty-eight silk producers and traders in east China's
Jiangsu Province established the Jiangsu Province Silk Group. The
province is one of the largest silk producers in China, accounting
for one-fourth of the country's total in terms of output and
export.
</P>
<P>
-- President Laurent-Desire Kabila of the Democratic Republic
of the Congo (DRC) wound up his state visit to China and left
Beijing yesterday.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily" (Business Weekly)
</P>
<P>
-- Steady economic growth and low inflation characterize
China's economic situation as 1997 draws to a close, and
economists anticipate that these trends will persist into the new
year.
</P>
<P>
-- China's money-masters met last week in Beijing to discuss
how to pool more revenue while targeting spending of the available
money on the most important areas.
</P>
<P>
-- A vast region of China's heartland rich in natural gas
resources will be the new promotion focus for massive foreign
investment. 
</P>
