<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, December 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran Saturday denied its reported readiness to issue
a written guarantee not to make any attempt on the lift of British
writer Salman Rushdie, who was condemned to death by Iran's late
spiritual leader Ayatollah Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
The British Independent newspaper reported Iran's Minister of
Culture and Islamic Guidance Ataollah Mohajerani has said Tehran
is ready to issue such a guarantee to spare the life of Rushdie,
accused of blasphemy to Islam for his novel the "Satanic Verses."
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance
said Mohajerani only reiterated the country's stand that the
decree by Khomeini is irrevocable, although the Iranian government
would not take actions against Rushdie.
</P>
<P>
The statement condemned the British daily for "distorting"
Mohajerani's remarks, saying "this new ploy has long been rejected
by Iranian and even European public opinions."
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi Deputy Premier Tariq Aziz Saturday lashed out
at chief U.N. arms inspector Richard Butler, calling his
statements "inaccurate and unobjective."
</P>
<P>
Aziz accused Butler of moving ahead "with a spree of inaccurate
and unobjective statements" on his Baghdad talks, thereby serving
the American plan aimed at unjustifiably scaling up the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Butler said on Friday in New York that he had reasons to doubt
that Iraq was hiding prohibited materials at "presidential and
sovereign sites."
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that U.N. arms inspectors had actually carried out
119 inspections of national security-related locations during
1996 and 1997 upon receiving information similar to those cited
in Butler's statements, but found nothing.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Striking U.S. pilots reached a tentative contract
agreement with Skyway Airlines Saturday soon after they stopped work.
</P>
<P>
The strike by 135 pilots for the Midwestern airline started at
4:05 a.m. (1005 GMT) for higher wages. As the two sides reached
an agreement on the contract, the pilots returned to work at about
5:30 a.m. But it was not clear what the detail of the agreement
was.
</P>
<P>
Skyway pilots are among the lowest paid in the industry with 50
percent earning less than 16,000 U.S. dollars annually, the union
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
