<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China County Benefits from Nuclear Plant, Officials Say </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Haiyan County on the northern
bank of Hangzhou Bay has benefited enormously from construction of
a nuclear power station nearby, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
The county in east China's Zhejiang Province has now grown into
one of China's top 100 counties for comprehensive economic
strength, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product (GDP) of the county has reached 4.2
billion yuan, and its total industrial and agricultural output is
10.8 billion yuan, with the industrial value making up 95 percent
of the total.
</P>
<P>
The officials attributed the county's economic boom to
construction of the Qinshan Nuclear Power Station, the country's
first of its kind. The station was first brought online in
December of 1991 with 300,000-kilowatt generating units.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 experts and officials from 30 countries and
regions came to visit or work in the county during the second and
third phases of construction. In the second phase two
600,000-kilowatt generating units were installed; in the third
phase, two 700,000-kilowatt units were added.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the county has had more than 80,000 domestic
tourists a year.
</P>
<P>
The exchanges have brought along qualified personnel,
technologies and information to Haiyan, and helped increase the
county's contacts and cooperation with the outside world, said the
officials.
</P>
<P>
While doing its best to support construction of the nuclear
power station and improving the infrastructure, Haiyan County has
built a 13.8-square-kilometer provincial-level economic
development zone for more than 100 businesses with an investment
of 600 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The county has worked toward an export-oriented economy. It
now has more than 100 overseas-financed companies with 178 million
U.S. dollars of foreign funding. The county exports 70 different
commodities and delivers 1.4 billion yuan in exports annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
