<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecclestone's F1 Monoply Questioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Karel Van Miert, the European
Union's Competition Commissioner, told the Flemish daily "Belang
van Limburg" on Saturday that he wanted to take measures under the
EU's competition rules against the monopoly of Bernie Ecclestone
in Formula One motor races.
</P>
<P>
Van Miert said that Mr. Ecclestone had had Formular 1 to
himself for 15 years and it was the time to set things right
according to rules.
</P>
<P>
Ecclestone received the exclusive right to manage all the
commercial aspects of races, including broadcasting 15 years ago
and for a length of 25 years.
</P>
<P>
The Commisson now sought comments from interested parties on
the accord under which FIA, the sport's ruling body, gives
Ecclestone's British company exclusive rights for Grand Prix motor
racing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
