<DOCNO> XIE19971221.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economy to Grow by Nine Percent This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to register
a GDP growth of nine percent this year with inflation around one
percent, according to today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
The paper says that the figures released by the State
Statistics Bureau (SSB) seem to indicate that China has "eluded
the spectre of a boom-and-bust cycle."
</P>
<P>
Nominal investment in fixed assets would be lower than in
previous years, but higher than GDP growth, while demand for
consumer goods would rise by a mild 10 percent, the paper says.
</P>
<P>
It is generally agreed that China has succeeded in achieving a
"soft landing" for its economy by modifying the speed of economic
growth to contain inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
The English language paper quotes Qiu Xiaohua, chief economist
at the SSB, as saying that if the current macro-economic
adjustments continue in the coming year, and significant disasters
and international turmoil are avoided, China's economy will
sustain rapid and steady growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
