<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Companies Installed More Software Piracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 20 (Xinhua) -- A growing number of new
business computer softwares used worldwide have been installed
illegally, according to the U.S. Software Publishers Association.
</P>
<P>
From sharing floppies to using boot-legged CDs, piracy will
cost software makers 14.5 billion U.S. dollars in lost sales this
year, estimates the Business Software Alliance, another U.S.
organization engaged in the research.
</P>
<P>
Many software pirates don't even know they're pirates. Earlier
this month, New York architectural firm MKDA paid 150,000 U.S.
dollars to settle copyright infringement charges brought by the
Business Software Alliance. In October, Fort Worth, Texas-based
Marketing Management Inc. paid 400,000 U.S. dollars to settle
similar charges.
</P>
<P>
Piracies occur mostly in smaller companies, which unknowingly
buy pirated items from resellers, according to researchers.
</P>
<P>
One problem is that softlifting isn't widely seen as a crime.
But penalties can be stiff. Fines can reach 100,000 U.S. dollars
per illegal copy, while commercial piracy is punishable by five
years in prison and 250,000 U.S. dollars in fines.
</P>
<P>
Experts suggest several ways for small companies to stay
legal, which include checking their sources, registering the
software with the manufacturer, and organizing software
management well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971221.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technology Training to Be Growing Industry in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 20 (Xinhua) -- A booming high-tech industry
in the United States has created opportunities for the development
of for-profit post-secondary education, the Investor's Business
Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The 600 billion U.S. dollars that U.S. institutions and
individuals spend on information technology is expected to triple
to 1.3 trillion dollars by 2001 and the high-tech industry is
demanding more skilled workers, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-five percent of the U.S. workforce is expected to compose
of skilled workers, 20 percent professional and 15 percent
unskilled by 2000, against 45 percent skilled, 20 percent
professional and 35 percent unskilled in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The trend is to be compounded with the widening pay gap, which
has grown from 25 percent in 1980 to 90 percent today between
college and high-school educated persons, a factor that has
induced more people to go to school for more training.
</P>
<P>
The paper said there may be two or three open slots for every
10 full-timers in five years as 95,000 more information technology
jobs are created each year, citing the figures of the research
group of Gartner.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, for-profit training schools enroll some 1.5
million students, 10 percent of the post-high-school education,
and have a revenue of 3.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
With a 20 percent increase of the number of high-school grads
forecast for the next decade and more students expected to come
back to training schools, the technology training industry has a
healthy outlook, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
