<DOCNO> XIE19971221.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, European Foreign Equity Ownership Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. and European investors
increased their foreign exposure to international equities in the
third quarter, overcoming a sharp drop in Asia-Pacific equity
holdings, a leading U.S. service company has found.
</P>
<P>
The total market value of U.S. holdings in international equity
securities jumped 5.1 percent or 27.8 billion U.S. dollars from
the end of the second quarter to 576.4 billion dollars, the
New-York based Technimetrics Inc. reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
European investors also saw their international equity
portfolios grow 3 percent or 12.3 billion dollars to 373.7 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Both U.S. and European investors decreased their investments in
Asian and Pacific markets in the first three quarters of the year
while increasing their international equity ownership in each
onther's market.
</P>
<P>
European equities comprised 62.3 percent of the total U.S.
international portfolio at the end of the third quarter, up from
58.8 percent at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
U.S. ownership of European stocks grew 36.5 billion dollars
from 322.5 billion dollars to 359 billion dollars while European
ownership of U.S. and Canadian stocks soared from 173.8 billion
dollars to 191.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Looking ahead, Technimetrics said U.S. and European investors
"may be bracing themselves for further setbacks" in their
Asian-Pacific portfolios given the stock market uncertainty and
financial unrest which have occurred in the region in the fourth
quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
